'''St Helen Witton Church, Northwich''' is in the centre of the town of [[Northwich]], [[Cheshire]], England ({{gbmapping|SJ665739}}).  It is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref name="images">{{citation  |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=57626 |title=Images of England: Church of St Helen, Northwich|accessdate=6&nbsp;August 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] }}</ref>  The church is now known as "St Helen's, Witton" or "Northwich Parish Church".<ref>{{citation  |url=http://sthelenwitton.org.uk/ |title=Parish of St Helen Witton, Northwich |accessdate=6&nbsp;August 2007  |publisher=Parish of St Helen Witton, Northwich }}</ref>  It is an active [[Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the [[diocese of Chester]], the archdeaconry of Chester and the deanery of Middlewich.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.chester.anglican.org/churches.asp| title = Churches in the Diocese| accessdate = 3&nbsp;May 2009| publisher = [[Diocese of Chester]]}}</ref>  [[Alec Clifton-Taylor|Clifton-Taylor]] includes it in his list of 'best' English parish churches.<ref>{{citation  | last =Clifton-Taylor | first =Alec | authorlink = Alec Clifton-Taylor | coauthors = | title =English Parish Churches as Work of Art |edition= | publisher =Batsford | date =1974 | location =London | page =240 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn =0 7134 2776 0 }}</ref>  
==History==

The church was originally a [[chapel of ease]] to [[Great Budworth]] and the area was then known as Witton.  The present building dates from the 14th century, with additions in the 15th, 16th and 19th centuries.<ref name="richards">{{citation  | last =Richards | first =Raymond | title =Old Cheshire Churches | publisher =Batsford | date =1947 | location =London | pages =360-364}}</ref>  

==Structure==

The church is built in red [[sandstone]] with flattish roofs concealed by parapets.<ref name="images"/>  The plan consists of a tower at the west end, a six-bay nave with north and south aisles, a chancel with a polygonal east [[apse]], a vestry to the north and a south porch.<ref name="salter">{{citation | last =Salter | first =Mark | title =The Old Parish Churches of Cheshire | publisher =Folly Publications | date =1995 | location =Malvern  | page =60 | isbn =1871731232 }}</ref>  The tower has four stages, is [[battlement|crenellated]] and has diagonal [[buttress]]es and a west door.  Above this is a four-light window, two-light bellringers' windows on the north and south faces, an empty [[niche (architecture)|niche]] on the west face, a clock with faces to all sides and paired two-light bell openings.<ref name="images"/>

==Fittings and furniture==

Over the nave and chancel is a continuous [[camber-beam]] and panel oak roof with diagonal cross-braces, large carved [[Boss (architecture)|bosses]] at the junctions of the main beams and smaller ones at the junctions of the secondary beams.<ref name="images"/>  There are no memorials of distinction and most of the old fittings were discarded in the 19th century restorations.  A 17th century altar table is still present.<ref name="richards"/>  The three-[[manual (music)|manual]] organ was built between 1870 and 1880 by Young & Son and later rebuilt by Charles A. Smethurst.<ref>{{citation  |url= http://www.npor.org.uk/cgi-bin/Rsearch.cgi?Fn=Rsearch&rec_index=N04353 |title= Northwich, Witton S Helen |accessdate=12&nbsp;August 2008  |publisher= [[British Institute of Organ Studies]] }}</ref>    The [[ring of bells|ring]] consists of eight bells cast by [[Taylors Eayre & Smith Ltd|John Taylor & Co]] in 1911.<ref>{{citation  |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=witton&Submit=++Go++&DoveID=NORTHWICH |title= Northwich, Witton S Helen |accessdate=12&nbsp;August 2008 |publisher= [[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] }}</ref>  The [[parish register]]s begin in 1561 and the [[churchwarden]]'s accounts date from the 17th century.<ref name="richards"/>  

==External features== 

In the churchyard is an 18th century red sandstone [[sundial]] with a copper dial which is listed Grade II.<ref>{{citation  |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/details/default.aspx?pid=1&id=57627 |title=Images of England: Sundial |accessdate=22&nbsp;October 2007 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] }}</ref> 

